eveloped} Charles D. Weller ANTIRUST LAW REPORT 11 March 2000.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See also \'93Dynamic efficiency is the most important beneficial effect of competition\'94 {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Empirical Evidence of the Benefits From Applying Competition Law} UNITED NATIONS CONFERENCE ON TRADE AND DEVELOPMENT, 24 November  UNCTAD report  p 8}}}
{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } or as they are otherwise known, \'93dynamic efficiencies\'94, because these are efficiencies to product or ser
vice quality - precisely those benefits competition seeks to induce.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Economists often speak of efficiencies as being of a \'93dynamic\'94 or \'93static nature\'94. Static efficiency may be further divided into allocative efficiency and productive efficiency. Allocative efficiency is defined as the allocation of products through the pr
ice system in the optimum manner required to satisfy consumer demand which will occur where the output of each product is at the level where the marginal cost of producing extra units equals their price. {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i UNCTAD REPORT, op cit} p5}}}
{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } Kattan argues that innovation has the quality of a public good in that its use by one party does not exclude others from using it simultaneously. He argues that despite protection afford
ed by intellectual property many innovations are imitated within a short time of their introduction.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See Kattan op cit pg 523. Kattan refers to various studies including recent work by Salop and Roberts who argue that certain efficiencies have a spillover effect because rivals replicate them over time.}}}
{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } Yet these efficiencies are also the hardest to quantify in practice.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See OECD report op cit pg 6. \'93 Dynamic efficiencies benefit consumers no  less than productive efficiencies but they are inherently more difficult to measure making their use more problematic in the trade off defence.\'94}}}
{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } At the other end of the scale are so called pecuniary efficiencies e.g. tax savings 
or lower input costs resulting from improved bargaining power with suppliers. These may be the easiest to \'93put a number\'94 to, but are not considered real savings in resources and are less favored.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 OECD report op cit pg 6. See also the Canadian Tribunal case of {\ul\ulc0 Commissioner v Superior Propane} U{\rtlchnpublished version dated 30 August 2000, }where the Commission argued that procurement claims by the merging forms that they could negotiate discounts in truck
 and freight rates were largely pecuniary. The Tribunal accepted this criticism and  rejected these claims in its assessment.}}}
{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } Production efficiencies are somewhere along the continuum b
etween innovation and pecuniary efficiencies. Production efficiencies are those efficiencies that permit firms to produce more output or better quality output from the same amount of input.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang1033\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs39\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 As Margaret Sanderson explains \'93 Production efficiencies include product-level, plant-level and multiplant-level operating and fixed cost efficiencies; savings associated with integrating new activities within the firm; and savings attributable to the tra
nsfer of superior production techniques and know-how from one of the merging parties to the other  Plant-level savings refer to those that flow from specialization, elimination of duplication, reduced downtime, smaller inventory requirements, or the avoida
nce of capital expenditures that would otherwise be required. Multiplant level savings include those associated with plant specialization, rationalization of administrative and management functions, and the rationalization of research and development activ
ities. Efficiencies also may be brought about in respect of distribution, advertising and raising capital. A reduction in transaction costs associated with integrating activities that previously were performed by third parties, such as contracting for inpu
ts, distribution and services, also may constitute production efficiencies.\'94 See Margaret Sanderson {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Efficiency Analysis in Canadian Merger Cases }ANTITUST LAW JOURNAL 623 (1997)}}}
